  "target_response": {
    "text": "Resting heart rate is how fast your heart beats when you're completely at rest, and it's one of the simplest fitness and recovery signals there is. Trends matter more than the raw number: as aerobic fitness improves, it usually drifts down over months, and a morning reading that sits noticeably above your own normal often flags fatigue, stress, poor sleep, alcohol, or an oncoming illness before you feel it. Since you log manually, there's no reading stored for you — but you don't need a device to get one. Count your pulse at your wrist for a full minute right after waking, before getting up, a few mornings a week. After a couple of weeks you'll have a personal baseline we can actually work with.",
